X chromosomes. &lt;br clear=3D&quot;non=\r\ne&quot;&gt;&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;For a woman, one X chromosome is inherited from her m=\r\nother and the other is from her father. The one from her father contains a =\r\nmix of his Y and X chromosome genes- in other words, she inherits his Y chr=\r\nomosome genes as much as any brother that she might have.&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;=\r\n&gt;&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;The SRY gene is responsible for producing a male. This =\r\ngene is on the Y chromosome and results in the formation of a male. But eve=\r\nn this gene is changed in each generation and incorporates some of the X ch=\r\nromosome genes with during DNA replication. &lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;&lt;br clear=3D=\r\n&quot;none&quot;&gt;So there is no such thing as an exclusively &#39;male&#39; gene or c=\r\nhromosome that is passed on from generation to generation.&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none=\r\n&quot;&gt;&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;In fact, we have an exclusively female piece of DNA th=\r\nat is passed on from generation to generation. This is called mitochondrial=\r\n DNA. Mitochondria are small energy producing centers inside every one of o=\r\nur cells. These do not undergo mixing with male DNA during formation of the=\r\n child. A man&#39;s mitochondrial DNA are not passed on at all to his child=\r\nren- only a blend of his X and Y chromosomes. Whereas a woman passes on a b=\r\nlend of her two X chromosomes, as well as her mitochondrial DNA to her chil=\r\ndren.&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;So I&#39;m afraid the chromosoma=\r\nl theory cannot be used to support a paternal lineage. In fact, it suggests=\r\n exactly the reverse - an exclusively maternal lineage through mitochondria=\r\nl DNA.&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;I do not think DNA necessarily =\r\ncan be used to predict lineage, and I like to feel like I belong equally to=\r\n\n both my mother&#39;s and father&#39;s lineage. When I do tarpanam I do it=\r\n lovingly for both maternal and paternal ancestors. In Kerala, where I come=\r\n from, we have a matrilineal system where women are the head of the family =\r\nand the children take the mother&#39;s name. These days, with nuclear famil=\r\nies, children tend to feel they belong equally to both parents. Unlike many=\r\n other parts of India, women are not seen as belonging to their husband&#39=\r\n;s family on being married. They always remain connected to their mother&#3=\r\n9;s family. &lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;There may be some esoteri=\r\nc reason for following a paternal lineage but chromosomes simply cannot be =\r\nused in that theory.&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;&lt;br clear=3D&quot;none&quot;&gt;Aparna&lt;/div&gt;\n\n   =\r\n &lt;/div&gt;\n     \n\n    \n    &lt;div style=3D&quot;color:#fff;min-height:0&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;=\r\n\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;div&gt;=\r\n&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n     \n\n    \n    &lt;div style=3D&quot;color:#fff=\r\n;min-height:0&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n&lt;/div&gt;\n\n\n\n  \n\n\n\n\n\n\n&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/d=\r\niv&gt;\n\r\n--089e0141a1a0cf492f05038d348e--\r\n\n"}}